<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Initiative: Great Addition or Gaming Nightmare: Part II<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 5, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Greetings once again. In my last article, I covered many of the basics involved with initiative as well some of the cards revealed. <br />
<br />
This time, I’m going to go into extensive detail on initiative. Since the remainder of the cards are spoiled and the next set is almost here, there is a much broader view of the concept and the effect it will have on the game. In this part, I will cover the Free Peoples side of initiative, while part 3 will cover the shadow and sites.<br />
<br />
Gimli, Faithful companion<br />
Text: While you have initiative, Gimli is strength +2.<br />
Str. 6<br />
Vit.3<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
This is a very potent version of Gimli. Unlike other initiative cards, this effect is permanent so long as you keep half your hand. This shouldn’t be incredibly difficult if half your hand is shadow cards. This is also one of the cards that can be useful without making initiative a focus of your deck. He’ll work with practically any strategy with the exception of perhaps swarm (since you’ll be striving to empty your hand). When it comes down to it, this card is a great gaming addition.<br />
<br />
Gimli’s Armor<br />
 Possession. Bearer must be Gimli.<br />
Text: Response: If you have initiative and Gimli<br />
Is about to take a wound, discard 2 cards from hand<br />
to prevent the wound.<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
This card works great with dwarf card drawing. Especially, with Gimli’s Helm. At the cost of a few cards per skirmish (or other instances if needed), you can make Gimli practically invincible. You can even take archery wounds on him and prevent them. You can prevent Blade Tip wounds, even. All Gimli needs now is something to make him defender +1. Gimli’s Armor is a great gaming addition.<br />
<br />
Legolas, Fearless Marksman<br />
Archer. Archery: If you initiative, discard 4<br />
cards from hand, to wound a minion.<br />
Str: 6<br />
Vit: 3<br />
Cost: 2<br />
<br />
This new Greenleaf works slightly different then his predecessor. Instead of exerting, you can to ditch half your hand to deal the wound. The main value of it appears to be that it allows you to still get the archery wound that you would normally not get with greenleaf. It allows cards such as Splendor to be used with him without affecting his text, thus allowing him to single-handedly deal 5 -6 archery wounds, however dumping half your hand is a high price to pay for 1 directed wound. Thus, imo, Legolas is not a very significant gaming addition without intense strategy as Greenleaf will nearly always be better. <br />
<br />
Gandalf, Manager of Wizards<br />
Text: Skirmish: Place 3 cards from your hand on<br />
top of your draw deck to make a minion skirmishing<br />
an unbound companion strength-3. Any shadow <br />
player may place 3 cards on top of his or her draw<br />
deck to prevent this.<br />
Str:7<br />
Vit:4<br />
Cost:4<br />
<br />
Perhaps, one of the biggest cards from the set isn’t readily obvious; this Gandalf does not directly relate to initiative, but it does relate to your hand, so I decided to mention him. At cost of 3 cards you can ‘servant’ any minion within the confines of unbound companions. The thing, though, is that you really aren’t paying a cost at all since you’ll be getting those cards back when you reconcile. Thus, it’s more like a deposit. You also have no limit on the number of times you can use his text (since you don’t need to have initiative); however your opponent can counter your ‘spell’ by fulfilling the same requirements. This is obviously a powerful strategy when your opponent likes to dump out as many minions as possible. This works well with Gandalf since he generally likes to flood the twilight pool, tempting your opponent all the more to use it and play more stuff. This Gandalf is a fabulous addition to the set, but loses much usefulness in multiplayer.<br />
<br />
Gollum, Plotting Deciever<br />
Text: If you have initiative during the shadow<br />
phase, you may play this minion from your<br />
discard pile.<br />
Str.5<br />
Vit:4<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
Basically, what it boils down to is that should your opponent get careless with their hand early on, then they will be menaced by this creature every turn. By himself, he isn’t a terrible threat, but coupled by some of his nasty conditions and events (i.e. Look At Him, Evil-Smelling Fens, Plotting, etc..), he can turn into something your opponent won’t want to tamper with. With the many other ways of getting Gollum out and back, you can make your opponent literally have to face Gollum at every site. Even if your opponent keeps their initiative, you can rig it with discarding cards such as ToBD or the Palantir. However, unless you’ve got support to back him with or are facing major archery trouble, this probably won’t be worth your effort. As much more subtle initiative related shadow card, but nonetheless potentially powerful, Gollum is a good addition to the set.<br />
<br />
Hobbitses Are Dead<br />
Event. Skirmish.<br />
Text: Spot Gollum or Smeagol to make a<br />
Nazgul, [Sauron] minion, or [Gollum] <br />
minion strength +2. If you have initiative,<br />
you may play this event from discard pile;<br />
place it under your draw deck instead of <br />
discarding it.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
The first Sauron pumper and it’s not even sauron culture. This event will go well with the Gollum mentioned above. A +2 pump for Nazgul is quite welcome as it can sometimes mean the difference between a wound and an overwhelm. Add that to the fact that you can immediately play it again if you have initiative (making it a potential +4 pump) as well as following turns where there is an opportunity, then it turns into a useful card. Gollum can even pump himself with it. It’s a fun and interesting new addition to the game and sort of reminds me of the ‘Watch Your Step’ days of SWCCG.<br />
<br />
Let Her Deal With Them<br />
Condition. <br />
Text: To play, spot Gollum or Smeagol. Bearer must <br />
be a minion. Limit 1 per minion. Bearer is damage +1. <br />
If you have initiative during the shadow phase, you may <br />
play this condition from your discard pile.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Believe it or not, but this is one of my favorite cards from the new set. It can be simply huge if applied to, say, a Nazgul, it could be a potentially devastating weapon, particularly on the fierce ones. When applied with other wonderful cards such as Nazgul Sword, and with the lack of stealth cards in ROTK, you can devastate opponent’s with this card. Let’s see, Cave Troll? He is now fierce and damage +2. Balrog is damage +3.<br />
You can make beasts out of some of those high powered besiegers. You could even implement it into a Uruk tracker deck. The fact that you can play it back again if you have initiative makes it about 10 times better than a cultured Lurtz’s Battle Cry. The only catch is that you have to spot Gollum. This shouldn’t be a problem with the many ways of getting him back. Being a good reason even by itself to integrate Gollum into specific decks, this card is a welcome addition to the set and to the game.<br />
<br />
Where Shall We Go<br />
Event. Skirmish<br />
Text: If you have initiative, discard 2 cards form<br />
hand to wound a minion smeagol is skirmishing<br />
twice. <br />
Cost:0<br />
<br />
Obviuosly a good choice for smeagol decks. A little restraint can go a long way. In this case, you can get rid of a lesser minion on poor Smeagol.  While most minions are more than 2 vitality, there are plenty of other ways to finish the job. It’s a good gaming addition, I think.<br />
<br />
Gondor has many other cards that do not state initiative, but relate to exact number of cards in hand (especially the companions). Some of these are decent and some are not so decent, but of those such cards, I will mention one in particular.<br />
<br />
Hasty Repairs<br />
Condition. Support Area<br />
Text: To play, spot 3 [Gondor] men. Regroup:<br />
While you have only 4 cards in hand, you<br />
may discard 2 cards from hand to play a [Gondor]<br />
fortification from your discard pile.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
This will be an important condition for knight decks. Fortunately, although it does require you to lose initiative, it does so in the regroup, where it is least likely to bite back at you. Since you obviously won’t have 4 cards once you discard 2, you can only do this once. Getting back fortifications, though, is quite key, so this is a great addition.<br />
<br />
Madril, Faramir’s Aid<br />
Text: Skirmish: If you have initiative, discard 2 cards <br />
from hand to wound a roaming minion Madril is<br />
skirmishing.<br />
Str.6<br />
Vit:3<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
He works pretty great for RBR wounding based decks. Basically, arm him with a Ranger Bow and he can pretty much kill anything, but then again, so can Mablung. So really the only advantage this guy has over Mablung is card cycling ability, which is not a bad thing at all. Due to initiative, this set has easily the most card cycling cards of any by far and this is just one such card. However, especially in the case of low vitality minions and late game where you have exhausted many of your companions, discarding 2 cards can be much more desirable than an exertion. Thus, it can be good addition.<br />
<br />
Stand to Arms<br />
Event. Skirmish<br />
Text: If you have initiative, discard 2 cards<br />
from hand to wound a roaming minion <br />
skirmishing a [Gondor] companion.<br />
<br />
A little more versatile than the Smeagol version, this could be a quite useful with conditions like Unexpected Visitor. Thus you can kill practically any minion on the bearer, then use the condition to make an easier double move. However, this event can pretty much be used in just about every situation. A fairly good addition.<br />
<br />
Deor<br />
Ally. Home 3K. Man.<br />
Villager. Text: Skirmish: If you have initiative, <br />
discard a card from hand to make a [Rohan] <br />
man strength +1.<br />
Str:4<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Leowyn<br />
Ally. Home 3K. Man.<br />
Villager. Text: Fellowship: If you have initiative,<br />
discard 2 cards from hand to heal a [Rohan]<br />
man.<br />
Str:4<br />
Vit:2<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Two Allies related to initiative. Deor is an excellent way of cycling cards and turning those unnecessary cards into pumps for your Rohan. Provided, it is small, but sometimes that is all that is needed to win a crucial battle. Of course, if a larger boost is needed, you can always raise the stakes and give yourself more. One of the most important things to note, though, is the easy cycling power he provides, which happens to be just what Rohan needs (like Rohan really needs to be more powerful). Leowyn charges a higher price for his services, but they are bigger. He can provide much needed healing, which is always welcome. Perhaps worth noting is his ability to heal any Rohan man, including allies. Since he doesn’t exert, he’s better than Guma as you can use him more than once per turn. In fact, with a full 8 card hand, you could use his text up to 3 times without losing initiative. These are both valuable assets to Rohan and excellent gaming additions.<br />
<br />
Guarded Fastness<br />
Event. Manuever.<br />
Text: If you have initiative, discard 2 cards from <br />
hand to heal all [Rohan] allies.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
Unless you use a lot of the original villagers, this isn’t worth a slot in your deck. You probably won’t heal more 2, which you could have already been healing anyway with Well Stored or something to that effect. The maneuver timing isn’t helpful either since it occurs before many of the allies have a chance to exert. This isn’t a very significant addition to the set and with so many better cards for Rohan and so few people even using allies, this card will probably never see any play.<br />
<br />
Riding Armor<br />
Possession. Armor.<br />
Bearer must be a [Rohan] man. <br />
Text: Response: If you have initiative and<br />
bearer is about to take a wound in a skirmish,<br />
discard 3 cards from hand to prevent the wound.<br />
Cost:1<br />
<br />
On the one hand, next to Lady of Rohan, this is the first wound protection Rohan gets. On the other hand, 3 cards from hand to prevent a wound can be steep. However, for companions like Eomer, whom Rohan players tend to rely a lot on, this card can be key for survival. Let’s not forget, the powerhouse has the big weakness that he has low vitality and no way to increase it, so it can definitely be a lifesaver. Being an effective way to keep your valuable companions alive, this is a decent addition to play.<br />
<br />
Sam, Resolute Halfling<br />
Text: Fellowship: If you have initiative, discard a card<br />
from hand to heal Sam. Response: If Frodo<br />
dies, make Sam the Ring-bearer (resistance 5).<br />
Str:3<br />
Vit:4<br />
Cost:2<br />
<br />
Due to his Frodo saving abilities, Sam’s game text is always short and sweet. Being very simple, this guy can be easily overlooked. For the few people who play Frodo/Sam/Smeagol decks, you will find this Sam quite refreshing. A Promise, as you know, cannot work if Frodo or Sam are exhausted. Thus, this Sam works quite well for fulfilling his part of the bargain. By simply playing SoD, he can fulfill Frodo’s as well. Anything that exerts a hobbit to play, you can put it on Sam, and heal him immediately.<br />
While I won’t go into detail on the various Hobbit exertion actions, I think it’s safe to say that Sam is a welcome addition to the game.  <br />
<br />
That’s about it for this part. As can be seen, ROTK has brought more cycling power than in any other set, by far, which means we’ll likely be seeing much bigger decks in the near future. Cycling cards has it’s risks, though, with shadow initiative becoming a very dangerous thing. In the next and final part, We’ll take a look at those and see which cards are beneficial to the game and which ones could get out of hand.<br />
